# jira-helper

A terminal **CLI** and importable **Python library** for admin work over
**Atlassian Cloud** (Jira today, Confluence later): resolve people ↔ Atlassian
account-ids, model a hierarchical org tree, and query/cache tickets (including
by org unit) for fast browsing, statistics, and reports.

> **Status: early release.** Live today — onboard with `init`, map people with
> `account`, model your org tree with `org`, query tickets with `issue list`
> (by assignee or org unit, created-date range, or raw JQL) / `issue get`, walk
> the parent tree with `issue roots` / `issue tree` / `issue list --roots`, shape
> virtual parent relationships with `rule`, and keep a local cache current with
> `sync` (incremental, idempotent) — once populated, the parent-tree reads run off
> the cache (one index scan instead of per-ancestor live calls) and inspect it
> with `cache`. Every run is logged (credentials redacted) to a rotating file you
> can read with `logs`. Still reporting *not implemented*: assigned-in-range date queries
> and Confluence. The full command surface is wired and self-describing
> (`--help`, `spec`); the shape is stable and the behavior fills in.

## Design

- **Library-first, 1:1 mapping.** Every command is a thin wrapper over a
  function: `noun` = module, `verb` = function. `jira-helper issue roots …` →
  `jira_helper.issue.roots(…)`. The CLI only parses args and renders; `--json`
  is a renderer flag, never a behavior change.
- **Resource-first nouns** modeled on `gh`/`kubectl`:
  `jira-helper [GLOBAL FLAGS] <noun> <verb> [args] [flags]`.
- **`--json` everywhere** for scripting, plus a machine-readable `spec` command
  that emits the entire command tree (every command, arg, flag, type, default,
  and a worked example + sample output) as JSON — built to be driven by an
  LLM/MCP wrapper in a single call.

## Command surface

```
jira-helper init | doctor | version          # onboarding, health, version
jira-helper spec [--json]                     # full command tree (LLM/MCP ingest)

jira-helper config  init|show|get|set|edit|verify|path
jira-helper account list|get|add|remove|search|path     # name ↔ account-id
jira-helper issue   list|roots|tree|get                 # ticket queries
jira-helper org     list|show|tree|members|create|move|rename|add-member|remove-member|delete|validate|edit|path
jira-helper rule    list|edit|add|remove|test|validate|path   # virtual-parent rules
jira-helper cache   status|get|export|clear|path        # local SQLite cache
jira-helper sync    run|status|install                  # background refresh
jira-helper logs    path|status|show|clear               # CLI log file (errors, debugging)
```

Global flags are defined once and precede the noun, e.g.
`jira-helper --json issue list --assignee alice`.

Run `jira-helper --help` (or `<noun> --help`) for the full, documented grammar.

## Quick start

```bash
# 1. onboard (writes ~/.config/jira-helper/config.yaml, chmod 600)
jira-helper init

# 2. confirm credentials + cache health
jira-helper doctor

# 3. map a person to their Atlassian account-id
jira-helper account search "Alice Kim"           # live lookup → candidate ids
jira-helper account add alice 5b10ac8d82e05b22cc  # record the mapping

# 4. query tickets
jira-helper issue list --assignee alice                 # one person
jira-helper issue list --assignee alice --assignee bob  # several
jira-helper issue list --created-from 2024-01-01 --created-to 2024-03-31
jira-helper issue list --jql 'project = PROJA AND statusCategory != Done'
jira-helper issue get PROJA-123
jira-helper --json issue list --assignee alice          # machine-readable
```

## Org hierarchy (`org`)

Model your org as a tree — `그룹 ▸ 부문 ▸ 실 ▸ 팀 ▸ 파트` (any depth; the `type`
label is free-form, so levels may be skipped). A unit's members are people from
the account store; querying a unit expands its **whole subtree** to those members'
tickets — so the same command serves "the whole office" and "one team".

```bash
# build the tree (parent must exist first; or `org edit` to bulk-author org.yaml)
jira-helper org create 플랫폼개발실 --type 실 --member 홍길동
jira-helper org create 서비스개발팀 --type 팀 --parent 플랫폼개발실 --member alice --member bob
jira-helper org create 인프라개발팀 --type 팀 --parent 플랫폼개발실
jira-helper org create 데이터파트 --type 파트 --parent 인프라개발팀 --member carol

jira-helper org tree                       # indented hierarchy
jira-helper org members 플랫폼개발실    # who a query will hit (subtree union)
jira-helper org validate                   # dangling parents / cycles / unresolved members

# tickets for everyone under the office, or just one team — same flag
jira-helper issue list --org 플랫폼개발실
jira-helper issue list --org 서비스개발팀
```

## Parent tree & virtual rules (`rule`)

Tickets form a tree via Jira's native parent links. `issue roots` collapses any
result set to the **root tickets** its members live under, `issue tree <KEY>`
shows the hierarchy around a ticket, and `--roots` is a modifier on any
`issue list`. On top of the native tree you can layer **virtual parents** — a
gitignored `rules.yaml` of conditional rules (first-match-wins) plus one-off
manual edges — so your own conventions become part of the hierarchy.

```bash
# roots of everything an assignee (or a whole org unit) is working on
jira-helper issue roots --assignee alice
jira-helper issue list --org 플랫폼개발실 --roots   # same, as a modifier

jira-helper issue tree PROJA-123        # hierarchy around one ticket

# virtual parents: a one-off manual edge, or author conditional rules
jira-helper rule add PROJA-101 PROJA-50 # PROJA-101's parent is PROJA-50
jira-helper rule edit                   # author conditional rules (rules.yaml)
jira-helper rule test PROJA-101         # which rule fires + the effective parent
jira-helper rule validate               # schema / ambiguity / cycle checks
```

## Background sync & cache (`sync` / `cache`)

`sync` fills a local SQLite cache so the parent-tree reads are instant. Point it at
the org unit(s) you care about via the `sync_orgs` config key; a run then caches
every ticket assigned to those units' members **plus the full ancestor chain of
each** (so epics/parents owned by others are present too), keyed off Jira's
`updated` field for cheap incremental re-runs.

```bash
jira-helper config set sync_orgs "플랫폼개발실"   # or a comma-list / a YAML list via `config edit`
jira-helper sync run                  # incremental (idempotent); --full for a clean rebuild
jira-helper sync status               # last run, watermark, lock state, last error
jira-helper sync install --launchd    # emit a launchd plist (or --cron) to schedule it

jira-helper cache status              # rows per product, last sync, size, schema version
jira-helper cache get PROJA-123       # one cached record
jira-helper --json cache export       # dump the cache for eyeballing / grep
```

Once the cache is populated, `issue roots` / `issue tree` / `rule test` read from it
automatically (and conditional-rule virtual descendants become enumerable). Pass
`--no-cache` to force a live walk, or a raw `--jql` (which the cache can't evaluate)
to fall back transparently.

## Logs & troubleshooting (`logs`)

Every run is logged to a rotating file under the config dir — by default
`~/.config/jira-helper/logs/jira-helper.log` — so a failure (including an
unexpected one) always leaves a trail you can read back. **Credentials are
redacted at write time**: the API token and the `Authorization` header never reach
the file. Other details (the Jira site URL, your email, account-ids, JQL) are kept
so the log is actually useful for debugging — review one before sharing it
publicly.

```bash
jira-helper logs path                 # where the log file lives
jira-helper logs status               # size, line count, time span, rotation backups
jira-helper logs show --lines 50      # tail the log
jira-helper logs show --level ERROR   # only errors (credentials already redacted)
jira-helper -y logs clear             # truncate the log + drop rotation backups
```

`-v`/`--verbose` additionally streams the log to stderr for live debugging.
Disable file logging entirely with `JIRA_HELPER_NO_LOG=1`, or relocate it with
`JIRA_HELPER_LOG_DIR=/path` (or a `log_dir` config key). The same file is also the
first thing to grab for a bug report — `tail`/`grep` it directly if the CLI itself
is too broken to run.

## Use as a library

```python
import jira_helper

jira_helper.account.add("alice", "5b10ac8d82e05b22cc")
jira_helper.org.create("서비스개발팀", type="팀", members=["alice"])
issues = jira_helper.issue.list(org=["플랫폼개발실"])   # whole-subtree expansion
one = jira_helper.issue.get("PROJA-123")
```

## Requirements

- Python 3.11+
- A Jira Cloud site (`https://your-domain.atlassian.net`)
- A Jira API token — create one at
  <https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens>

## Installation

### Install / update (recommended)

[`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) installs the tool from a public distribution
index over plain, anonymous HTTPS — no GitHub login or token required (handy on
locked-down networks where authenticated access is blocked). First install `uv`:

```bash
curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh
```

Then install — and later upgrade — `jira-helper`:

```bash
# install
uv tool install jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/

# upgrade to the latest release
uv tool install --force jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/
```

For one-word upgrades, add an alias to `~/.zshrc`:

```bash
alias jh-up='uv tool install --force jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/'
```

`--index` keeps PyPI as the default, so runtime dependencies (typer, httpx,
PyYAML) resolve from PyPI while `jira-helper` itself comes from the distribution
index. This assumes PyPI is reachable over HTTPS.

### From a clone (development)

```bash
pip install -e .
```

Either way you get the `jira-helper` console entry point.

## Configuration

Authentication uses Jira Cloud **basic auth** with your account email + an API
token (the token is **not** your password). Two ways to provide it, in order of
precedence:

1. **Interactive** — `jira-helper init` writes `config.yaml` (chmod 600) under
   `$JIRA_HELPER_CONFIG` → `~/.config/jira-helper/`. Inspect/edit it later with
   `jira-helper config show` / `config set <key> <value>` / `config verify`.
2. **Environment variables** — override (or replace) the file at read time:

   | Variable         | Description                              |
   | ---------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
   | `JIRA_BASE_URL`  | e.g. `https://your-domain.atlassian.net` |
   | `JIRA_EMAIL`     | The Atlassian account email              |
   | `JIRA_API_TOKEN` | API token (NOT your password)            |

Env vars win over the file, so CI or a throwaway shell can run without `init`.

> Never commit credentials. The config file and `.env` are git-ignored, and the
> token is masked by `config show`/`get` unless you pass `--reveal`.

## Development

```bash
pip install -e '.[dev]'
ruff check .
ruff format .
pytest
```

## Releasing (maintainer)

The version is derived from git tags by `setuptools-scm`, so a tag push **is** the
release: GitHub Actions builds the wheel and publishes it to the distribution
index over GitHub Pages.

```bash
git tag v0.2.0
git push origin v0.2.0
```
